{"parse":{"title":"Velificatio","pageid":30730141,"revid":850505649,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:352px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tellus_-_Ara_Pacis.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Tellus_-_Ara_Pacis.jpg/350px-Tellus_-_Ara_Pacis.jpg\" width=\"350\" height=\"226\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Tellus_-_Ara_Pacis.jpg/525px-Tellus_-_Ara_Pacis.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Tellus_-_Ara_Pacis.jpg/700px-Tellus_-_Ara_Pacis.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2178\" data-file-height=\"1404\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Tellus_-_Ara_Pacis.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>A pair of <i>velificantes</i> on the <a href=\"/wiki/Ara_Pacis\" title=\"Ara Pacis\">Augustan Altar of Peace</a> (late 1st century BC)</div></div></div>\n<p><i><b>Velificatio</b></i> is a stylistic device used in <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_art\" title=\"Roman art\">ancient Roman art</a> to frame a <a href=\"/wiki/List_of_Roman_deities\" title=\"List of Roman deities\">deity</a> by means of a billowing garment. It represents \"vigorous movement,\" an <a href=\"/wiki/Theophany\" title=\"Theophany\">epiphany</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> or \"the vault of heaven,\" often appearing with celestial, weather, or sea deities.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> It is characteristic of the <a href=\"/wiki/Iconography\" title=\"Iconography\">iconography</a> of the <a href=\"/wiki/Aura_(mythology)\" title=\"Aura (mythology)\">Aurae</a>, the Breezes <a href=\"/wiki/Personification\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Personification\">personified</a>, and one of the elements which distinguish representations of Luna, the Roman <a href=\"/wiki/Moon_goddess\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Moon goddess\">goddess of the Moon</a>, alluding to her astral course.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>A figure so framed is a <i><b>velificans</b></i> (plural <i><b>velificantes</b></i>). Not all deities are portrayed as <i>velificantes</i>, but the device might be used to mark a member of the <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_Emperor\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Roman Emperor\">Imperial family</a> who had been divinized (a <a href=\"/wiki/Divus\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Divus\"><i>divus</i> or <i>diva</i></a>).<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><i>Velificatio</i> is a frequent device in Roman art,<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> including painting, <a href=\"/wiki/Mosaic\" title=\"Mosaic\">mosaic</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Relief\" title=\"Relief\">relief</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Roman_sculpture\" title=\"Roman sculpture\">sculpture</a>, though it poses technical difficulties for freestanding sculpture. The Athenian sculptor <a href=\"/wiki/Praxiteles\" title=\"Praxiteles\">Praxiteles</a> was able to achieve it.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> The term is also used to describe <a href=\"/wiki/Hellenistic_art\" title=\"Hellenistic art\">Hellenistic art</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> The device continued to be used in later <a href=\"/wiki/Western_art_history\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Western art history\">Western art</a>, in which it is sometimes described as an <i>aura</i>, \"a breeze that blows from either without or from within that lifts the veil to reveal the face of an otherwise invisible being.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Usage_and_examples\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Usage and examples</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#List_of_velificantes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">List of <i>velificantes</i></span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#See_also\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Usage_and_examples\">Usage and examples</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Velificatio&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Usage and examples\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Classical_Latin\" title=\"Classical Latin\">classical Latin</a>, the <a href=\"/wiki/Abstract_noun\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Abstract noun\">abstract noun</a> <i>velificatio</i> is uncommon,<sup id=\"cite_ref-9\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-9\">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> and refers to the act of setting sail, from <i>velum</i>, \"sail\" (but also \"cloth, garment, veil\") and the <i>-fic-</i> combining element from <i>-ficio, -ficere</i> (= <i>facio, facere</i>, \"do, make\"). The verbal form was the basis for modern scholarly usage. <a href=\"/wiki/Pliny_the_Elder\" title=\"Pliny the Elder\">Pliny</a> describes <i><a href=\"/wiki/Aura_(mythology)\" title=\"Aura (mythology)\">Aurae</a> velificantes sua veste</i>, the Breezes \"making a sail with their own garment\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-10\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-10\">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> at the <a href=\"/wiki/Porticus_Octaviae\" title=\"Porticus Octaviae\">Porticus Octaviae</a> (\"<a href=\"/wiki/Portico\" title=\"Portico\">Portico</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Octavia_the_Younger\" title=\"Octavia the Younger\">Octavia</a>\").<sup id=\"cite_ref-11\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-11\">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> Such depictions of the Aurae are known from extant Roman art, and have been used as comparative material to identify the pair of <i>velificantes</i> in a scene from the <a href=\"/wiki/Ara_Pacis\" title=\"Ara Pacis\">Augustan Altar of Peace</a>. On the basis of a passage from the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Carmen_Saeculare\" title=\"Carmen Saeculare\">Carmen Saeculare</a></i> of <a href=\"/wiki/Horace\" title=\"Horace\">Horace</a>, composed and performed for <a href=\"/wiki/Augustus\" title=\"Augustus\">Augustus</a>'s staging of the <a href=\"/wiki/Saecular_Games\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Saecular Games\">Saecular Games</a> in 17 BC, the central figure is often identified as Tellus (Earth):\n</p>\n<blockquote><p>Fertile in produce and cattle, let Tellus grant Ceres a crown of grain; let the healthful waters and breezes of Jove nourish offspring.<sup id=\"cite_ref-12\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-12\">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup></p></blockquote>\n<p>Not all scholars agree on this analysis of the scene. The creatures on which the <i>velificantes</i> are seated also suggest <a href=\"/wiki/Nereids\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nereids\">Nereids</a>, and the reference may point to the <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Cult_of_the_Nymphs&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Cult of the Nymphs (page does not exist)\">Cult of the Nymphs</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-13\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-13\">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The significance of the veil is sometimes explained in terms of the <a href=\"/wiki/Initiation_rite\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Initiation rite\">initiation rites</a> of the <a href=\"/wiki/Mystery_religions\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Mystery religions\">mystery religions</a>. Initiates wore drapery or a veil which was lifted by a priestess. The veil was a symbol of death, and its removal in the rite signified the initiate's rebirth. The <i>velificatio</i> thus appears in scenes on <a href=\"/wiki/Sarcophagi\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Sarcophagi\">sarcophagi</a> and in other <a href=\"/wiki/Funerary_art\" title=\"Funerary art\">funerary art</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-14\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-14\">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<ul class=\"gallery mw-gallery-traditional\">\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Villa_dei_Misteri_V_-_2.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Villa_dei_Misteri_V_-_2.jpg/85px-Villa_dei_Misteri_V_-_2.jpg\" width=\"85\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Villa_dei_Misteri_V_-_2.jpg/127px-Villa_dei_Misteri_V_-_2.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Villa_dei_Misteri_V_-_2.jpg/170px-Villa_dei_Misteri_V_-_2.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2201\" data-file-height=\"3107\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Villa_of_the_Mysteries\" title=\"Villa of the Mysteries\">Villa of the Mysteries</a> (1st century).\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:34px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:The_Kidnapping_of_Europa_Mosaic.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/The_Kidnapping_of_Europa_Mosaic.jpg/120px-The_Kidnapping_of_Europa_Mosaic.jpg\" width=\"120\" height=\"82\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/The_Kidnapping_of_Europa_Mosaic.jpg/180px-The_Kidnapping_of_Europa_Mosaic.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/The_Kidnapping_of_Europa_Mosaic.jpg/240px-The_Kidnapping_of_Europa_Mosaic.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2760\" data-file-height=\"1889\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Europa_(mythology)\" title=\"Europa (mythology)\">Europa</a> (mosaic, 1st-2nd century)\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Proserpina_kidnapped_Kircheriano_Terme.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Proserpina_kidnapped_Kircheriano_Terme.jpg/90px-Proserpina_kidnapped_Kircheriano_Terme.jpg\" width=\"90\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Proserpina_kidnapped_Kircheriano_Terme.jpg/135px-Proserpina_kidnapped_Kircheriano_Terme.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Proserpina_kidnapped_Kircheriano_Terme.jpg/180px-Proserpina_kidnapped_Kircheriano_Terme.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1700\" data-file-height=\"2270\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Pluto_(mythology)\" title=\"Pluto (mythology)\">Pluto</a> (cinerary urn, 2nd century).\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:16px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Clipeus_Selene_Terme.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Clipeus_Selene_Terme.jpg/120px-Clipeus_Selene_Terme.jpg\" width=\"120\" height=\"118\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Clipeus_Selene_Terme.jpg/180px-Clipeus_Selene_Terme.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/04/Clipeus_Selene_Terme.jpg/240px-Clipeus_Selene_Terme.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1530\" data-file-height=\"1500\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Selene\" title=\"Selene\">Selene</a> (<a href=\"/wiki/Clipeus\" title=\"Clipeus\">clipeus</a> from a <a href=\"/wiki/Sarcophagus\" title=\"Sarcophagus\">sarcophagus</a>, early 3rd century).\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:24px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Sousse_neptune.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/Sousse_neptune.jpg/120px-Sousse_neptune.jpg\" width=\"120\" height=\"102\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/Sousse_neptune.jpg/180px-Sousse_neptune.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/68/Sousse_neptune.jpg/240px-Sousse_neptune.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1800\" data-file-height=\"1530\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Neptune_(mythology)\" title=\"Neptune (mythology)\">Neptune</a> (mosaic, 3rd century).\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:French_Empire_mantel_clock.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/French_Empire_mantel_clock.jpg/89px-French_Empire_mantel_clock.jpg\" width=\"89\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/French_Empire_mantel_clock.jpg/134px-French_Empire_mantel_clock.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7b/French_Empire_mantel_clock.jpg/179px-French_Empire_mantel_clock.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"2669\" data-file-height=\"3581\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/French_Empire_mantel_clock\" title=\"French Empire mantel clock\">French Empire mantel clock</a>  (1822) depicting the nereid Galatea.\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"List_of_velificantes\">List of <i>velificantes</i></span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Velificatio&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: List of velificantes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The <i>velificatio</i> motif may be found with numerous deities, divine beings, and <i>divi</i>, including:<sup id=\"cite_ref-15\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-15\">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Enl%C3%A8vement_d%27Europe_by_N%C3%B6el-Nicolas_Coypel_(detail).jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Enl%C3%A8vement_d%27Europe_by_N%C3%B6el-Nicolas_Coypel_%28detail%29.jpg/220px-Enl%C3%A8vement_d%27Europe_by_N%C3%B6el-Nicolas_Coypel_%28detail%29.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"303\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Enl%C3%A8vement_d%27Europe_by_N%C3%B6el-Nicolas_Coypel_%28detail%29.jpg/330px-Enl%C3%A8vement_d%27Europe_by_N%C3%B6el-Nicolas_Coypel_%28detail%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Enl%C3%A8vement_d%27Europe_by_N%C3%B6el-Nicolas_Coypel_%28detail%29.jpg/440px-Enl%C3%A8vement_d%27Europe_by_N%C3%B6el-Nicolas_Coypel_%28detail%29.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"725\" data-file-height=\"1000\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Enl%C3%A8vement_d%27Europe_by_N%C3%B6el-Nicolas_Coypel_(detail).jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>Enl\u00e8vement d'Europe</i> (1726\u201327) by <a href=\"/wiki/No%C3%ABl-Nicolas_Coypel\" title=\"No\u00ebl-Nicolas Coypel\">No\u00ebl-Nicolas Coypel</a></div></div></div>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Nyx\" title=\"Nyx\">Nyx</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Aura_(mythology)\" title=\"Aura (mythology)\">Aura</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Nereids\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Nereids\">Nereids</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Horae\" title=\"Horae\">Horae</a> (Seasons)</li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Maenad\" title=\"Maenad\">Maenads</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Niobids\" title=\"Niobids\">Niobids</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Niobe\" title=\"Niobe\">Niobe</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Selene\" title=\"Selene\">Selene</a> or Luna<sup id=\"cite_ref-16\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-16\">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Helios\" title=\"Helios\">Helios</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Caelus\" title=\"Caelus\">Caelus</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-17\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-17\">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Europa_(mythology)\" title=\"Europa (mythology)\">Europa</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Dionysus\" title=\"Dionysus\">Dionysus</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Ariadne\" title=\"Ariadne\">Ariadne</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Poseidon\" title=\"Poseidon\">Poseidon</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Neptune_(mythology)\" title=\"Neptune (mythology)\">Neptune</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Amphitrite\" title=\"Amphitrite\">Amphitrite</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Aphrodite\" title=\"Aphrodite\">Aphrodite</a> or <a href=\"/wiki/Venus_(mythology)\" title=\"Venus (mythology)\">Venus</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Mars_(mythology)\" title=\"Mars (mythology)\">Mars</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-18\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-18\">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Tarpeia\" title=\"Tarpeia\">Tarpeia</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-19\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-19\">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Vibia_Sabina\" title=\"Vibia Sabina\">Vibia Sabina</a><sup id=\"cite_ref-20\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-20\">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Velificatio&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Halo_(religious_iconography)\" title=\"Halo (religious iconography)\">Halo (religious iconography)</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Aureola\" title=\"Aureola\">Aureola</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Aura_(paranormal)\" title=\"Aura (paranormal)\">Aura (paranormal)</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Velificatio&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap mw-references-columns\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Paul Rehak, <i>Imperium and Cosmos: Augustus and the Northern Campus Martius</i> (University of Wisconsin Press, 2006), p. 111.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Robert Turcan, <i>Les religions de l'Asie dans la vall\u00e9e du Rh\u00f4ne</i> (Brill, 1972), p. 21.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\